      <div class="container">
        <h2 id="cultureHeading" class="h3">Culture & Working Principles</h2>
        <p class="text-muted">GPIS is built on a horizontal structure and mutual trust. Below are the central elements of our culture.</p>

        <div class="row g-4">
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="card card-contrast h-100 p-3" role="article" aria-labelledby="culture-structure">
              <h3 id="culture-structure" class="h5">Structure & Collaboration</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Horizontal structure — leadership and members operate as equals.</li>
                <li>Strong mutual trust encourages autonomy and inclusive decision-making.</li>
                <li>Highly collaborative; welcoming participation at all engagement levels.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="card card-contrast h-100 p-3" role="article" aria-labelledby="culture-guiding">
              <h3 id="culture-guiding" class="h5">Guiding Principles</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Social impact and constant innovation guide daily work.</li>
                <li>Emphasis on translating science to real-world population health benefits.</li>
                <li>Commitment to exploring novel methods — from data collection to analysis.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="col-12">
            <div class="card card-contrast p-3" role="article" aria-labelledby="culture-challenges">
              <h3 id="culture-challenges" class="h5">Operational Challenges (Transparent)</h3>
              <p class="mb-0">We recognize constraints that affect our throughput and learning environment:</p>
              <ul class="mt-2">
                <li><strong>Voluntary basis:</strong> members are unpaid — projects are not primary occupations.</li>
                <li><strong>Communication:</strong> mainly via Google Meet; documentation and tracking need improvement.</li>
                <li><strong>Project management:</strong> incomplete prioritization and follow-up due to lack of a dedicated manager.</li>
                <li><strong>Student mentorship:</strong> goal to strengthen structured mentorship and training opportunities.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- PRIMARY PROJECT -->
    <section id="project" class="py-5 bg-light" aria-labelledby="projectHeading">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 id="projectHeading" class="h3">Primary Project — 2019 Rio Grande Birth Cohort</h2>
        <p class="text-muted">A fixed, prospective, population-based cohort from a middle-income country studying life-course epidemiology of mental health and its intergenerational transmission.</p>

        <div class="row g-4">
          <div class="col-lg-8">
            <article class="card card-contrast p-3" role="article" aria-labelledby="project-desc">
              <h3 id="project-desc" class="h5">Project description</h3>
              <p>The cohort includes <strong>2,051 mothers and their infants</strong> born in Rio Grande in 2019 and is designed to examine mental health trajectories across the life course and mechanisms of intergenerational transmission.</p>

              <h4 class="h6 mt-3">Key findings</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Significant increase in maternal mental health problems during the COVID-19 pandemic: a <strong>six-fold increase</strong> in depressive symptoms and a <strong>three-fold increase</strong> in anxiety compared to baseline.</li>
              </ul>

              <h4 class="h6 mt-3">Subprojects</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Use of wearable cameras and AI-powered facial recognition to analyze mother–child interactions.</li>
                <li>Evaluation of effects of the <strong>2024 floods in Rio Grande do Sul</strong> on maternal and child mental health.</li>
              </ul>

              <h4 class="h6 mt-3">Key collaborators</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Rebecca Pearson</strong> — Manchester Metropolitan University (MMU), leader of MHINT (observational & computational methods).</li>
                <li><strong>Ana Luiza Goncalves Soares</strong> — University of Bristol (life course epidemiology & advanced longitudinal analyses).</li>
                <li><strong>Marc Bornstein</strong> — Eunice Kennedy Shriver National Institute of Child Health and Human Development (child development & family studies).</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="mt-3">
                <button class="btn btn-outline-primary" id="openMoreProject" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="projectMore">Read project notes</button>
              </div>

              <div id="projectMore" class="collapse mt-3" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="card-body p-2">
                  <p class="mb-0">The cohort's multidisciplinary subprojects emphasize combining traditional epidemiologic analyses with computational and observational techniques to enhance understanding of parent–child dynamics in LMIC settings.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </article>
          </div>

          <div class="col-lg-4" aria-hidden="false">
            <div class="card card-contrast p-3">
              <h3 class="h6">Project metadata</h3>
              <ul class="list-unstyled mb-0">
                <li><strong>Design:</strong> Fixed prospective, population-based cohort</li>
                <li><strong>Sample size:</strong> 2,051 mother–infant dyads</li>
                <li><strong>Geography:</strong> Rio Grande, Brazil</li>
                <li><strong>Topical focus:</strong> Maternal & child mental health; intergenerational mechanisms</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

